      <div xml:id="NA192-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">iḵtu iravukkuṟi maṟukkappaṭṭu āṟṟāṉāya (ET: ākiya) talaimakaṉ colliyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is what HE said who was unable to bear it when he had been refused night trysts.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA192">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            kuruti vēṭkai yurukeḻu vayamāṉ</l>
<l>            valimiku muṉpiṉ maḻakaḷiṟu pārkku</l>
<l>            marampayil cōlai maliyap pūḻiya</l>
<l>            ruruvat turuvi ṉāṇmēya lāru</l>
<l>            māri yeṇkiṉ malaiccura nīḷiṭai </l>
<l>            nīnayantu varuta levaṉeṉap palapulan</l>
<l>            taḻutaṉai yuṟaiyu mammā varivai</l>
<l>            payaṅkeḻu palaviṉ kollik kuṭavaraip</l>
<l>            pūtam puṇartta putitiyal pāvai</l>
<l>            virikati riḷaveyiṟ ṟōṉṟi yaṉṉaniṉ </l>
<l>            ṉāynala muḷḷi variṉemak</l>
<l>            kēma māku malaimuta lāṟē.</l>
            </lg>
       <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>        O you pretty dark young woman who remains crying(?)<note place="foot">Line 6 is a somewhat curious mixture of the 2nd and 3rd person. What is the relation between the form given here: <term xml:lang="ta">aḻuntaṉai uṟaiyum</term>, and another one found rather frequently: <term xml:lang="ta">aḻutu-uṟaivi</term>?</note>,</l>
<l rend="indent">        very vexed [by the thought]: “what of your longing [for me and] coming</l>
<l rend="indent2">        the long way through the mountainous desert of the bear in the shower</l>
<l rend="indent3">        that becomes full preying early in the day on the beautiful sheep</l>
<l rend="indent3">        of the Pūḻiyar(?)<note place="foot">Syntax and wording are strange and the impact is doubtful. Why not have <term xml:lang="ta">eṇku</term> inside the <term xml:lang="ta">ārum</term> construction, which is the usual position of the subject in such clauses? What of <term xml:lang="ta">māri</term>? Is it an elliptical reference to the colour of the bear, a bear [dark as] a rain-cloud? And T.V.G. reads the thing in a completely different way: "the desert of ... bears that become full, feeding in the morning like the beautiful sheep of the Pūḻiyar". But that would presuppose that sheep are black and bears occur in large numbers, neither of which is particularly likely.</note>, while there are many groves dense with trees,</l>
<l rend="indent4">        where the beautiful strong animal with a demand for blood<note place="foot">This is certainly a metaphor for the tiger, and T.V.G. interprets <term xml:lang="ta">uru-keḻu</term> as "inducing fear" here.</note></l>
<l rend="indent4">        peers out for the infant elephant bull formerly of much strength”</l>
<l>    – joyful is for us the way along the foot of the mountain,</l>
<l rend="indent2">        remembering [your] choice goodness,</l>
<l rend="indent3">        as the appearance of the young sunlight with unfolding rays,</l>
<l rend="indent3">        as the newly arising doll put together by the spirits(?)<note place="foot">The references to this <term xml:lang="ta">pāvai</term> on Kolli mountain are varied and seemingly contradictory. Sometimes it seems to be a picture of a female deity, drawn on the mountain side and worshipped, sometimes awe-inspiring, sometimes benign. Here it rather seems to be a doll (if the character of <term xml:lang="ta">iyal</term> as a verb of movement is interpreted correctly). T.V.G. affirms that it is a kind of walking image, send by the gods to delude and destroy some demon fiends.</note></l>
<l rend="indent4">        on the west mountain of Kolli with richly yielding jack-trees.</l>
    
        </lg>
